{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604235"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:50:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:50:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.08,0.05,0.03,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"2955"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11151"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is reviewed on the medical ward after routine blood tests reveal a sodium of 152 mmol/L (135-145). She was admitted one day ago with pyelonephritis which is clinically improving. She has a history of bipolar disorder and takes lithium and sertraline. In addition, she is receiving IV amoxicillin-clavulanate for her infection, maintenance IV fluids and taking ondansetron for associated nausea. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly lethargic but is alert and oriented. Her pulse rate is 108/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Her mucous membranes are dry. Her urine output over the past 24 hours has been 4.2 L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to the hypernatraemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lithium","Sertraline","Intravenous amoxicillin/clavulanate","Ondansetron","Normal saline"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hypernatraemia and polyuria while taking lithium. \u003Cstrong\u003ELithium\u003C/strong\u003E is well known to cause nephrogenic diabetes insipidus by interfering with aquaporin-2 water channels in the collecting duct, reducing the kidney\u0027s ability to concentrate urine in response to antidiuretic hormone. This results in excessive free water loss and subsequent hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E and other selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors can cause syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH), which typically leads to hyponatraemia rather than hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOndansetron\u003C/strong\u003E and other antiemetic medications do not directly affect sodium homeostasis or cause significant polyuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous amoxicillin/clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E itself does not typically cause significant changes in sodium levels, though the vehicle in which it is delivered may contribute to fluid balance changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal saline\u003C/strong\u003E administration can contribute to hypernatraemia if given in excess, but the patient\u0027s high urine output and the temporal relationship with chronic lithium therapy make this a less likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of lithium-induced nephrogenic diabetes insipidus includes ensuring adequate free water intake, considering dose reduction or alternative mood stabilisers if possible, and potentially using amiloride which can help reduce lithium accumulation in collecting duct cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lithium causes nephrogenic diabetes insipidus by reducing the kidney\u0027s response to antidiuretic hormone.","Hypernatraemia in hospitalised patients is often iatrogenic and requires careful medication review."],"references":["Liamis G, Filippatos TD, Elisaf MS. Evaluation and treatment of hypernatremia: a practical guide for physicians. Postgrad Med. 2016;128(3):299-306. doi: 10.1080/00325481.2016.1147322. Epub 2016 Feb 23. PMID: 26813151.","Sonani B, Naganathan S, Al-Dhahir MA. Hypernatremia. [Updated 2023 Aug 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441960/","Liamis G, Milionis HJ, Elisaf M. A review of drug-induced hypernatraemia. NDT Plus. 2009 Oct;2(5):339-46. doi: 10.1093/ndtplus/sfp085. Epub 2009 Jul 16. PMID: 25949338; PMCID: PMC4421386."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T09:30:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T09:31:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8496"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0